    <td align="left" valign="top"><!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Main text" --> 
      <H3><FONT face="Tahoma, sans-serif">About this site</FONT></H3>
      <P><B>Joseph Dalton Hooker</B> was arguably the most important British botanist 
        of the nineteenth century. A traveller and plant-collector, he was one 
        of Charles Darwin&#146;s closest friends and eventually became director 
        of Britain&#146;s Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew.</P>
      <P>The image on the left is believed to be  the last photograph ever taken of Sir J.D. Hooker, June 3rd 1911. (&copy; The Trustees of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew.).<br>
        <br>
        These pages are intended to provide some basic information about Joseph 
      Hooker. They include: </P>
      <UL>
        <LI>November 2012: Jim Endersby will be in New Zealand talking about Hooker, on Novermber 27th (<a href="http://www.aucklandmuseum.com/248/what's-on" title="Auckland Museum" target="_blank">Auckland</a>) and 29th (<a href="http://www.bellee.co.nz/preview/hewitson/_pdf/Brochure-JohnBuchannanSymposium.pdf" title="Buchanan Symposium" target="_blank">Dunedin</a>). You can hear an interview with Jim Endersby on NZ radio <a href="http://podcast.radionz.co.nz/sat/sat-20121117-0935-jim_endersby_imperial_science-048.mp3" title="Radio interview" target="_blank">here</a>.</LI>
        <LI>May 2012: there's an interview with this site's author, Jim Endersby, about his book <em>Imperial Nature</em> on the <a href="http://newbooksinscitechsoc.com/2012/05/23/jim-endersby-imperial-nature-joseph-hooker-and-the-practices-of-victorian-science-university-of-chicago-press-2008/" title="New Books Network" target="_blank">New Books Network</a> site.</LI>
        <LI>2011 marks the centenary of Hooker's death; a special event was organised at the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew. A special edition of the Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society that celebrates Hooker's life is now <a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/(ISSN)1095-8339/homepage/joseph_dalton_hooker_virtual_issue.htm" title="Great Linnean" target="_blank">freely available online</a>.</LI>
        <LI>You can hear (and even see) the site's author, Jim Endersby, talking about Hooker at the Royal Society, via <a href="http://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/the-royal-society-audio-podcasts/id105000706#" target="_blank">a free podcast on iTunes</a>. </LI>
        <LI>Jim Endersby's book <em><a href="Imperial Nature.html">Imperial Nature: Joseph Hooker and the practices of Victorian Natural History</a></em>, is now out in paperback from the University of Chicago press.</LI>
        <LI>more detailed <A href="biography1.htm"
					onMouseOver="self.status='A brief biography of Joseph Hooker';return true"
					onMouseOut="self.status='Welcome to the Joseph Hooker website';return true">biographical
             notes</A>, including  details of <a href="Hooker%27s%20family.htm">Hooker&#8217;s
        immediate family</a>.</LI>
        <LI>Information about Hooker&#146;s <A href="collectors1.htm"
					onMouseOver="self.status='Information on collectors and correspondents';return true"
					onMouseOut="self.status='Welcome to the Joseph Hooker website';return true">collectors 
          and correspondents</A> in Australia and New Zealand,</LI>
        <LI> A selection of Hooker&#146;s <A
				  href="writings.htm">writings</A>.</LI>
        <LI><A href="links1.htm"
				  onMouseOver="self.status='Internet resources for information on Hooker, natural history and botany';return true"
				  onMouseOut="self.status='Welcome to the Joseph Hooker website';return true">links 
          to web resources</A> that contain information about Hooker, the history 
          of botany in general and the history of natural history more generally</LI>
        <LI>A guide to some of the <A href="archives.htm"
					onMouseOver="self.status='Archives on Hooker and his correspondents';return true"
					onMouseOut="self.status='Welcome to the Joseph Hooker website';return true">archival
             sources</A> concerning Hooker, including an <strong><font color="#FF0000"></font></strong> <a href="/archives_Kew.htm">online
             catalogue of Kew&#8217;s Hooker papers</a>.</LI>
        <LI> A guide to <A href="sources1.htm">published sources</A> about Hooker.</LI>
        <LI> You can <A href="Search.htm">search</A> this site.</LI>
        <LI>If you would like to know about Jim Endersby, who runs this site, <a href="http://www.jimendersby.com/" target="_blank">click here for a link to my website</a>. </LI>
      </UL>
      <P></P>
      <P>This site is no longer being updated regularly.</P>
